---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const places = [
  {
    src: "/images/atlas-of-worlds/luxon-dream-bc1962.jpg",
    title: "Sanctuary of Light",
    subtitle: "The palace of the Enlightenment God",
  },
  {
    src: "/images/atlas-of-worlds/forest-mountains-be20f7.png",
    title: "The Road to Khra'lov'nyss",
    subtitle: "Adventurers stumble across a path that wasn't there this morning",
  },
  {
    src: "/images/atlas-of-worlds/vineyard-ea2346.jpg",
    title: "Stormvinter Winery",
    subtitle: "In a plane between the Abyss and the Fire Plane, ash falls like rain",
  },
  {
    src: "/images/atlas-of-worlds/magical-city-6a1edc.png",
    title: "Glissandir, city of Ljósálfar High Elves",
    subtitle:
      "The Ljósálfar who live here believe it is as close to a 'heaven' as one can get in life",
  },
  {
    src: "/images/atlas-of-worlds/allowaks-santuary-da3fa0.jpg",
    title: "The Village of Silkeayd",
    subtitle: "A nest of arctic miscreants and outcasts",
  },
  {
    src: "/images/atlas-of-worlds/strazcabur-63eec9.png",
    title: "The Village of Strážcabúr",
    subtitle:
      "Hidden in the Ashkeeper Peaks, and a well-kept secret from the rest of the world",
  },
  {
    src: "/images/atlas-of-worlds/under-the-mountain-db0588.jpg",
    title: "The inside of a mystical shop known as \"Under the Mountain's Shadow\"",
    subtitle: "Where you can buy anything under the mountain's shadow",
  },
  {
    src: "/images/atlas-of-worlds/ashkeeper-peaks-temple-aa991c.png",
    title: "Abandoned temple in the Ashkeeper Peaks",
    subtitle: "Previously used to worship Khra'lov'nyss, the Blue Great Wyrm",
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title="The Atlas of Worlds — Annalisa Ard"
  description="A sampling of locations and characters designed to evoke player engagement and emotional investment."
>
  <section class="section atlas-intro">
    <h1>The Atlas of Worlds, and a Chorus of Voices</h1>
    <p class="intro-text">
      Every place is a question a world asks, and is answered by narrative
      design. Below is a sampling of some of the locations I have created for
      the worlds I breathed into existence, crafted around the silent
      questions of the adventuring path.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section atlas-gallery">
    <ul class="gallery">
      {
        places.map((p) => (
          <li class="gallery-item">
            <div class="img-wrap">
              <img src={p.src} alt={p.title} loading="lazy" />
              <figcaption class="caption-over">
                <span class="caption-title">{p.title}</span>
                <span class="caption-sub">{p.subtitle}</span>
              </figcaption>
            </div>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="section atlas-philosophy">
    <p>
      Each successful project begins with active listening and empathetic
      inferences; I focus on understanding the problem, aligning the process
      with end-goals, finding the right tone, and building something honestly
      immersive, genuinely engaging, and expressive by nature. The result is
      work that feels grounded, made to connect, inspire, and hold meaning
      over time.
    </p>
    <p>
      Every one of these locations exist in its world as an answer to a
      question the story has not yet learned to ask. As the narrative
      designer, I am constantly looking for what is not there, listening for
      what the narrative hungers for when it feels too certain, too straight,
      too safe. I build places that challenge the path forward: sanctuaries
      for faith to falter, crossroads for destiny to bend, ruins where beauty
      decays into truth. Each environment becomes a mirror for emotion —
      wonder when the tale grows weary, sorrow when it loses depth, defiance
      when it demands resolve. My process aligns empathy with architecture,
      tone with intent, creating spaces that feel both inevitable and alive.
      The result is work that connects, inspires, and endures — worlds that
      breathe not because they are written, but because they remember why
      they were built.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section chorus-heading">
    <h2>Every hero begins with a heartbeat</h2>
  </section>

  <section class="section chorus-body">
    <p>
      In my work, characters are never passengers in the plot; they are the
      plot. Their fears and hungers, the secrets they protect and the truths
      they cannot outrun become the invisible currents that tug the world
      into motion. Every choice they make, every flaw they carry, distorts
      the shape of fate. Their internal contradictions are not background
      details but the emotional physics that govern the rise and fall of
      entire storylines.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Chorus of Voices highlights some of the characters I crafted as
      living engines of narrative, each one a center of gravity with the
      power to alter destinies. My process begins at the core: uncovering a
      character's original wound, the fracture that defines how they see
      themselves and their world. From there, I trace the lines of tension —
      how they resist their history, how they ache for something more, and
      how that private struggle radiates outward into friendships, enmities,
      cultures, and even the mythic fabric of the setting itself. These
      voices — heroes, villains, martyrs, monsters, skeptics, dreamers —
      become a symphony of intent and consequence, each heartbeat shaping
      the rhythm of the tale that follows.
    </p>
    <p>
      Meaning is born not only from who these characters are, but from how
      they collide. A gentle word between allies can redirect a war; a lie
      told at the wrong moment can collapse a kingdom. Love becomes a
      lighthouse; resentment becomes a storm. Every bond, warm or wounding,
      deepens the world, giving it emotional resonance that no map or
      timeline could achieve on its own. Through this web of relationships,
      players and readers don't just witness the story; they enter it,
      threading themselves into the living architecture of connection,
      conflict, and catharsis.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is the heart of my narrative design: a world carried forward by
      the people who inhabit it. A chorus of voices, each with a story worth
      hearing, each with the power to reshape the world — one heartbeat at
      a time.
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .atlas-intro {
    padding-top: 6vh;
    padding-bottom: 2vh;
    max-width: 1280px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  .atlas-intro h1 {
    margin-bottom: 0.5em;
    max-width: 900px;
  }
  .intro-text {
    font-size: 1.4em;
    max-width: 1100px;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.92);
    margin: 0;
  }
  .atlas-gallery {
    padding-top: 5vh;
    padding-bottom: 6vh;
  }
  .gallery {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    gap: 1vw;
  }
  @media (max-width: 1100px) {
    .gallery {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    }
  }
  @media (max-width: 800px) {
    .gallery {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    }
  }
  @media (max-width: 520px) {
    .gallery {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
  .gallery-item {
    margin: 0;
  }
  .img-wrap {
    position: relative;
    width: 100%;
    aspect-ratio: 1 / 1;
    overflow: hidden;
    background: #111;
  }
  .img-wrap img {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;
    display: block;
    transition: transform 0.6s ease, filter 0.6s ease;
    filter: brightness(0.85);
  }
  .gallery-item:hover .img-wrap img {
    transform: scale(1.05);
    filter: brightness(1);
  }
  .caption-over {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    justify-content: flex-end;
    padding: 1.2em 1em 1em;
    background: linear-gradient(
      to top,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.85) 0%,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5) 45%,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0) 80%
    );
    opacity: 0;
    transition: opacity 0.3s ease;
    color: #fff;
  }
  .gallery-item:hover .caption-over {
    opacity: 1;
  }
  .caption-title {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.15em;
    font-weight: 700;
    line-height: 1.25;
    margin-bottom: 0.3em;
  }
  .caption-sub {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 0.95em;
    font-weight: 300;
    line-height: 1.4;
    color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.85);
  }

  .atlas-philosophy {
    padding-top: 6vh;
    padding-bottom: 4vh;
    max-width: 1100px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  .atlas-philosophy p {
    font-size: 1.4em;
    line-height: 1.65;
    margin-bottom: 1.2em;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .chorus-heading {
    padding-top: 6vh;
    padding-bottom: 2vh;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .chorus-heading h2 {
    font-size: 2.5em;
    margin: 0 auto;
    max-width: 800px;
  }
  .chorus-body {
    padding-top: 2vh;
    padding-bottom: 8vh;
    max-width: 1100px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  .chorus-body p {
    font-size: 1.4em;
    line-height: 1.65;
    margin-bottom: 1.3em;
  }
</style>
